<subSubSection id="7E83FE90F869FF86FF378B1E75E7FC3B" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="3626AD1BF869FF86FF378B1E7079FD1F" blockId="13.[189,310,629,655]" box="[189,310,629,655]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<heading id="6D6E1A77F869FF86FF378B1E7079FD1F" bold="true" box="[189,310,629,655]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" reason="3">
<emphasis id="04ED7109F869FF86FF378B1E7079FD1F" bold="true" box="[189,310,629,655]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3626AD1BF869FF86FF378BCC75E7FC3B" blockId="13.[189,1400,679,939]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
The genus may be distinguished by the following characters: antennal segment I bottle-shaped, with a distinctly narrowed basal part, somewhat longer than vertex width; head, pronotum and scutellum with dense coarse punctures; pronotum with collar flat and not delimited posteriorly, calli notably expanded, with posterior depression, disc strongly raised, covering mesonotum, basal half of scutellum and bases of hemelytra; disc of pronotum with narrow, impunctate, whitish carina along midline; legs long and thin, with all femora somewhat swollen apically; hemelytra slightly constricted on basal fourth, with costal margin sinuate, concave on basal half and nearly straight apically (
<figureCitation id="AEA2B19EF869FF86FB908AFB75D3FC3B" box="[1050,1180,912,939]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="47.[189,232,1894,1920]" captionTargetBox="[218,1361,434,1799]" captionTargetId="figure-12@47.[189,1398,393,1855]" captionTargetPageId="47" captionText="Fig. 6. Dorsal view and label data of type specimens. A–C. Jessopocoris scutellatus Carvalho, 1981, ♀, holotype, AMNH_PBI 00340984, BMNH(E) 1633131, NHM. D–F. Lopidolon pallescens Poppius, 1911, ♀, holotype, FMNH, currently retained at AMNH. G–J. Loidolon sordidus Poppius, 1911, ♀, holotype, HNHM." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4690374" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4690374/files/figure.png" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Fig. 6A–B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="7E83FE90F869FF86FF378ABE7010F99F" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="3626AD1BF869FF86FF378ABE7060FC7F" blockId="13.[189,303,981,1007]" box="[189,303,981,1007]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<heading id="6D6E1A77F869FF86FF378ABE7060FC7F" bold="true" box="[189,303,981,1007]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" reason="3">
<emphasis id="04ED7109F869FF86FF378ABE7060FC7F" bold="true" box="[189,303,981,1007]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Remarks</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3626AD1BF869FF86FF378D6C7238FABF" blockId="13.[189,1400,1031,1328]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<bibRefCitation id="5208D0EAF869FF86FF378D6C70C0FBB2" author="Carvalho J. C. M." box="[189,399,1031,1058]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="479 - 484" refId="ref21106" refString="Carvalho J. C. M. 1981 b. On three new genera and four new species of Miridae from India and Oceania (Hemiptera). Revista Brasileira de Biologia 41: 479 - 484." type="journal article" year="1981">Carvalho (1981b)</bibRefCitation>
described a single female from Ranikhet, northern 
<taxonomicName id="F199D698F869FF86FC7D8D6C7579FBB1" baseAuthorityName="Poppius" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[1015,1078,1031,1057]" class="Liliopsida" family="Orchidaceae" genus="India" kingdom="Plantae" order="Asparagales" pageId="13" pageNumber="37" phylum="Tracheophyta" rank="genus">India</taxonomicName>
, as a new species and new monotypic genus 
<taxonomicName id="F199D698F869FF86FE1F8D4573FEFBD7" authorityName="Carvalho" authorityYear="1981" box="[405,689,1069,1095]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Jessopocoris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scutellatus">
<emphasis id="04ED7109F869FF86FE1F8D4573FEFBD7" box="[405,689,1069,1095]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Jessopocoris scutellatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. He noted that the new genus differs from all other genera by the shape of pronotum, strongly expanded posteriorly and covering a substantial part of scutellum. Subsequently, 
<bibRefCitation id="5208D0EAF869FF86FEE18D107370FB05" author="Mu Y. - R. &amp; Liu G. - Q." box="[363,575,1147,1173]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" pagination="47 - 54" refId="ref22439" refString="Mu Y. - R. &amp; Liu G. - Q. 2012. New records of the genus Jessopocoris Carvalho, 1981 (Hemiptera: Miridae: Bryocorinae), with descriptions of two new species found in China. Zootaxa 3573 (1): 47 - 54. https: // doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3573.1.5" type="journal article" year="2012">Mu &amp; Liu (2012)</bibRefCitation>
described two more species of the genus from 
<collectingRegion id="F45D63F9F869FF86FBF78D1075ADFB05" box="[1149,1250,1147,1173]" country="China" name="Guangxi" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Guangxi</collectingRegion>
and 
<collectingRegion id="F45D63F9F869FF86FA948D107437FB05" box="[1310,1400,1147,1173]" country="China" name="Yunnan" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Yunnan</collectingRegion>
provinces of 
<collectingCountry id="4E8EED8BF869FF86FED68DCA70E9FB2B" box="[348,422,1185,1211]" name="China" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">China</collectingCountry>
. According to the original description, both Chinese species of 
<taxonomicName id="F199D698F869FF86FB2A8DC97477FB2B" authorityName="Carvalho" authorityYear="1981" box="[1184,1336,1186,1211]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Jessopocoris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="04ED7109F869FF86FB2A8DC97477FB2B" box="[1184,1336,1186,1211]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Jessopocoris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have a boat-shaped, non-modified genital capsule, a large, L-shaped left paramere located in an entirely closed paramere socket and apparently absent right paramere. The only Indian species of the genus, 
<taxonomicName id="F199D698F869FF86FF378C7D7019FABF" authorityName="Carvalho" authorityYear="1981" box="[189,342,1301,1327]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Jessopocoris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="scutellatus">
<emphasis id="04ED7109F869FF86FF378C7D7019FABF" box="[189,342,1301,1327]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">J. scutellatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, is still known only from the female 
<typeStatus id="E92213B9F869FF86FC828C7E723CFABF" box="[776,883,1301,1327]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">holotype</typeStatus>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="3626AD1BF869FF86FF378C307010F99F" blockId="13.[188,1399,1370,1551]" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">
<taxonomicName id="F199D698F869FF86FF378C30701AFAE4" authorityName="Carvalho" authorityYear="1981" box="[189,341,1371,1396]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Jessopocoris" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="04ED7109F869FF86FF378C30701AFAE4" box="[189,341,1371,1396]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Jessopocoris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is superficially similar to 
<taxonomicName id="F199D698F869FF86FD0C8C30724CFAE4" authorityName=", Distant" authorityYear="1911" box="[646,771,1371,1396]" class="Insecta" family="Miridae" genus="Ernestinus" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hemiptera" pageId="13" pageNumber="14" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="04ED7109F869FF86FD0C8C30724CFAE4" box="[646,771,1371,1396]" italics="true" pageId="13" pageNumber="14">Ernestinus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
spp. due to the body proportions, raised and punctate pronotal disc and uniformly brown to dark brown coloration on the clavus, transverse spot on the medioapical part of corium, apex of cuneus and cells contrasting with the whitish-yellow remaining part of hemelytron and legs. However, it clearly differs from that genus in all other characters mentioned in the diagnosis.
</paragraph>
